{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658701"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:53:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20812"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20812"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96853"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13687"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20812"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79467"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11579"},{"type":"tags","id":"12645"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96853"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGenes located physically close to each other on a chromosome tend to be inherited together, a phenomenon known as genetic linkage.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes linkage disequilibrium?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Random assortment of genes during meiosis","Non-random association of alleles at different loci","Equal distribution of alleles in a population","Balanced expression of linked genes on chromosomes","Complete separation of linked genes during crossing over"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-random association of alleles at different loci\u003C/strong\u003E accurately describes linkage disequilibrium. This genetic phenomenon occurs when specific allele combinations at different loci appear together more frequently than would be expected by random chance. Such associations can persist across generations, especially for genes in close physical proximity on a chromosome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom assortment of genes during meiosis\u003C/strong\u003E describes Mendel\u0027s law of independent assortment, which applies to genes on separate chromosomes, not linkage disequilibrium.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual distribution of alleles in a population\u003C/strong\u003E refers to Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, not linkage disequilibrium, which specifically involves unequal distribution of allele combinations.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBalanced expression of linked genes on chromosomes\u003C/strong\u003E relates to gene expression patterns rather than inheritance, and does not describe linkage disequilibrium.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete separation of linked genes during crossing over\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts linkage disequilibrium, which persists because recombination has not fully separated the linked alleles.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELinkage disequilibrium has significant applications in genetic mapping studies and genome-wide association studies, enabling researchers to identify disease-associated genetic markers without complete genome sequencing. While genetic recombination eventually breaks down linkage disequilibrium, this process may require many generations, particularly for tightly linked genes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Linkage disequilibrium occurs when alleles at different loci appear together more frequently than expected by chance.","Genetic recombination during meiosis gradually breaks down linkage disequilibrium over successive generations.","Linkage disequilibrium is valuable for disease gene mapping and population genetic studies."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 1-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79467"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79467"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T08:45:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T08:49:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13687"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96853"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11579"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genome and epigenome","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:10+10: